<DOC><DOCNO> AP901211-0064 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-11-90 1150EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Austria-SovietAgent     12-11 0229</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Austria-Soviet Agent,0249</SECOND><HEAD>Alleged Soviet Agent Detained in Salzburg</HEAD><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A suspected Soviet agent was detained inSalzburg today after receiving documents about U.S. weapons systemsfrom an informant who escaped into a crowd of Christmas shoppers,officials said.   The arrested man hada Soviet diplomatic passport and claimed tobe accredited at the embassy in Vienna, senior intelligenceofficial Karl Koenig said in a telephone interview from Salzburg.   Police detained the unidentified 39-year-old man on a Salzburgstreet after he was given a thick envelope by another man, Koenigsaid. The contact man escaped in the late morning Christmas bustleand traffic, he said.   Koenig said police acted on confidential information.   The detained man is allegedly an officer of the Soviet militaryintelligence GRU, but police refused to identify him while they tryto determine his name and the validity of his diplomatic passport.   Koenig said police were unable to reach anyone at Vienna'sSoviet Embassy.   A spokesman at the embassy who did not identify himself told TheAssociated Press he knew nothing of the incident and couldtherefore not comment.   Koenig said the material in the envelope included materialsabout U.S. weapons categories, technical know-how, and the U.S.space agency NASA. He said the material was all in English and wasbeing sent to the prosecutor's office.   If the man is a diplomat accredited in Austria, he would have tobe released because of diplomatic immunity.</TEXT></DOC>